So imagine 20 cartons of that book chirping at you.

37:11.184 --> 37:12.867
I love that.

37:12.887 --> 37:14.589
Did you go to the book expo?

37:14.649 --> 37:16.191
I haven't gone in a couple of years.

37:16.311 --> 37:18.013
I go to it when it's in New York.

37:17.993 --> 37:19.995
Well, it's been in Chicago.

37:20.556 --> 37:26.422
I always scare people because I walk into the booth and they'll say, I work for a literacy organization.

37:26.502 --> 37:27.183
I'm a salesperson.

37:27.403 --> 37:29.746
Yeah, because they figure you're looking for handouts, right?

37:29.926 --> 37:32.649
Yeah, so my second sentence is, we buy the books.

37:33.310 --> 37:35.292
Oh, great.

37:35.312 --> 37:36.713
Well, that might be nice of you giving this.

37:37.034 --> 37:39.536
I hope I didn't deprive you of your copy.

37:39.837 --> 37:40.938
No, I have a second copy.

37:40.958 --> 37:41.959
That's very kind.

37:41.979 --> 37:42.740
Thank you.

37:42.760 --> 37:47.545
Yeah, so it's mostly a matter of money, and

37:47.693 --> 37:49.716
of getting the books we want.

37:49.736 --> 37:51.458
And most of your funding comes from where?

37:51.638 --> 37:52.099
Is it?

37:52.259 --> 37:54.482
Federal, state, grants.

37:54.562 --> 37:56.404
We'll take money from pretty much anyone.

37:56.765 --> 37:58.247
And how large is the staff here?

37:58.968 --> 38:01.531
It's 20 full-time, part-time people.

38:01.551 --> 38:06.718
And this is the national headquarters, of course, so you're buying, basically, for everyone.

38:06.738 --> 38:09.501
Well, they choose one book.

38:09.521 --> 38:14.848
And then we have some people who really love to wheel and deal with the publishers, and they go off and do their own thing.

38:14.980 --> 38:21.890
If they fundraise money of their own or if they choose the reimbursement option, they can go buy the books whatever they like.

38:22.111 --> 38:28.300
But I would say 98% of people choose to have a prepaid account sent up.

38:30.023 --> 38:40.078
And now that the economy has taken, took a downturn, I need to be pursued by publishers who just want to be part of it.

38:40.098 --> 38:43.603
Because as we get larger and better known, people are realizing

38:44.326 --> 38:47.571
They give away three million books a year.

38:48.432 --> 38:49.954
We need to be part of this.

38:50.695 --> 38:51.336
This is a market.

38:51.396 --> 38:56.704
It's astonishing that it's taken them so long to discern that.

38:57.105 --> 39:05.457
Well, publishers are still very much in the mindset of we deal with bookstores.

39:06.365 --> 39:09.969
And so they're still calling it special sales when it's outside of a bookstore.

39:09.989 --> 39:11.551
Yeah, and it doesn't even count in your numbers.

39:11.571 --> 39:18.178
I mean, for the author, I'll bet the author really gets stung on that a little bit.

39:19.560 --> 39:20.501
But for this, I wouldn't mind.

39:20.901 --> 39:23.204
We'd hope to get something out of it.

39:23.644 --> 39:24.185
Oh, yeah.

39:24.205 --> 39:32.194
And I wouldn't want to deprive an author or a publisher of making a profit on the book, because that means they get to publish the next book.

39:32.334 --> 39:32.594
Sure.

39:33.575 --> 39:36.118
But shall we scare them off a little bit?

39:36.470 --> 39:39.995
by walking in and saying 80%.

39:40.015 --> 39:48.726
We negotiate a bit, and if we can find out if they're doing a print run of the book we want, we'll pack our order onto it, and that makes it a little bit easier.

39:48.746 --> 39:53.792
80%, when you think about it, it's not that bad, because there's no distributor that they're paying.

39:53.872 --> 39:55.114
There's no bookstore.

39:55.855 --> 40:01.021
And so their margin is really not going to be, it's going to be a difference of 10 or 15%, maybe.

40:01.362 --> 40:02.003
And no returns.

40:02.083 --> 40:02.804
And no returns.

40:04.065 --> 40:05.447
How can you possibly beat that?

40:05.630 --> 40:06.952
It's pretty good, actually.

40:07.253 --> 40:14.505
Well, the part that makes it difficult for them is because the purchase order is coming from Scholastic.

40:14.525 --> 40:14.666
Mm-hmm.

40:14.686 --> 40:26.927
And even though publishing is a very interactive business with other publishers, the idea of having to sell to Scholastic at that discount just... Yeah, I know.

40:26.987 --> 40:30.172
But they see your numbers, so it has to have... Yeah.

40:30.192 --> 40:31.114
Anyway, they'll come around.

40:31.516 --> 40:36.581
Yeah, so they start smelling the money, and I actually just had to call off one of the publishers.

40:38.363 --> 40:45.651
They read in our newsletter about a huge grant that our person up in Alaska thought.

40:45.671 --> 40:49.134
And so the next thing I know is this guy's following me.

40:49.155 --> 40:50.376
Do you know anything about this?

40:51.417 --> 40:52.658
And he's naming the publisher to me.

40:53.679 --> 41:01.067
I just got this thing about buying books from them, and Paul doesn't know anything about purchasing books.

41:01.385 --> 41:09.976
He was just going to deal with us and Scholastic because we have a way of dealing with very huge, very big purchases.

41:11.578 --> 41:20.590
And I was a little bit nipped because I had told the sales rep, if you do anything big, I need to know about it.

41:20.870 --> 41:23.554
And so I called her and she was a little surprised.

41:23.714 --> 41:26.858
And I had to tell her, this is not a big universe.

41:27.919 --> 41:29.081
Especially the book world.

41:29.101 --> 41:30.683
There's such a cottage industry as that.

41:30.832 --> 41:32.595
Everybody knows what's going on.

41:32.975 --> 41:40.085
Yes, um, Harry actually met Harriet Zefert, who's got her own publishing company now.

41:40.105 --> 41:41.387
Had to talk.

41:41.407 --> 41:42.329
That's her husband.

41:42.469 --> 41:43.771
That's Harriet's husband.

41:43.791 --> 41:44.552
Oh, that's funny.

41:45.353 --> 41:47.136
No, they just started their own publishing company.

41:47.176 --> 41:48.898
That's cute.

41:48.918 --> 41:50.701
Yeah.

41:50.721 --> 41:51.362
That's wonderful.

41:52.463 --> 41:59.153
Well, I think we've had a great start, and I will contact.

41:59.173 --> 42:00.535
Pardon me.

42:02.000 --> 42:09.030
Ron Bailey is the Director of National Programs for Reach Out and Read.

42:09.410 --> 42:29.779
Well, I was just saying that one of the interesting things about interviewing staff here is that all the people who send their resumes, even for the most technical of jobs, and we have quite a few of those now, really are interested in books and they're interested in reading and have a strong belief that reading was

42:30.839 --> 42:32.501
a really important part of their lives.

42:33.301 --> 42:42.771
So it's wonderful in the interviews because you can always start the conversation that way about the love of reading and your shared love of reading.

42:42.791 --> 42:50.359
If you start talking with them about SQL databases, which is really what they're going to be doing later, it's a shift.

42:50.479 --> 42:54.423
But you always have that base in talking to people who want to work here.

42:55.664 --> 42:56.485
It's wonderful.

42:56.525 --> 42:58.246
And they end up here, which is good.

42:58.266 --> 43:00.829
So what's your background or how do you come as a

43:01.383 --> 43:07.513
First of all, I was a kindergarten teacher for many, many years and ran a private kindergarten in D.C.

43:07.894 --> 43:21.335
And then went back to graduate school and actually studied instructional design, focusing on how you train adults in the workplace, how you actually retrain people while they're working.

43:21.436 --> 43:27.205
And this was a really interesting project for me because we were trying to

43:27.370 --> 43:37.419
to retrain doctors in their workplace, and it's challenging because they have no time for one thing, and the other thing is that they believe they don't have anything else to learn.

43:39.081 --> 43:50.852
So how we teach doctors some of the stuff that every good kindergarten or preschool teacher knows is what I'm about.

43:51.152 --> 43:54.255
And give me a couple of examples of what you mean, what kinds of things you have to treat.

43:54.455 --> 44:00.281
Well, you know, things like book language.

44:00.301 --> 44:01.823
You used this word, book language.

44:02.083 --> 44:10.172
Every teacher knows that book language is different from conversational language, and doctors have never stopped to think about that.

44:10.792 --> 44:19.922
When you read aloud to children, there's a cadence to book language that is different.

44:20.594 --> 44:34.688
Or the fact that when you're reading to children, if you, you know, your eyes or your finger sort of lead you to this left-right sequence, every teacher knows that.

44:35.209 --> 44:40.074
And doctors don't, you know, there was no place in their education to learn that.

44:40.334 --> 44:43.097
And so this ended the equation because?

44:43.778 --> 44:48.222
Because you want them to understand why they're doing this, that kids

44:48.505 --> 45:00.661
Kids who are in preschool or kids who are affluent and are read to a lot have the advantage of this book language before they get to kindergarten, even before they get to preschool.

45:00.681 --> 45:07.410
And kids from families that don't read to their kids don't have that experience.

45:07.430 --> 45:17.584
So if the doctor can pass on even the tiniest amount of this information to parents about what reading aloud gets for the kids,

45:17.885 --> 45:20.228
it's really important.

45:20.248 --> 45:27.316
And also if you can grab them with those ideas of, well, they just haven't thought much about it, really.

45:29.178 --> 45:33.203
So, tell me a little bit about the programs that you used to do.

45:33.223 --> 45:33.504
Yeah.

45:34.485 --> 45:43.576
Well, my job is really to keep us going in now 2075 clinics and hospitals across the country.

45:44.296 --> 45:44.837
And we're

45:45.914 --> 45:50.959
The interesting part, I think, is that we're a tiny part of any one of those clinics.

45:50.979 --> 46:01.150
I mean, we're probably 150th of what they do, and we have to insinuate ourselves in there in some way.

46:01.190 --> 46:15.465
First for the training piece, first for getting even an hour with a group of pediatricians and nurses to train them in some of these basics, and then to teach them a little bit about

46:15.952 --> 46:22.359
how to use our grant, which we give to them, and how to raise some money on their own for books to sustain their program.

46:22.419 --> 46:39.879
So I have a staff of six, and that's, you've got Jackie, who's in charge of organizing that training effort, and she deploys about 100 regional trainers who are all physicians who go out and do training for us.

46:41.280 --> 46:42.702
And then we have a

46:43.205 --> 46:50.372
a very sophisticated database which sort of keeps track of the sites and our grants to them.

46:52.254 --> 46:58.560
We are an interesting organization in that we're always raising money for ourselves.

46:58.861 --> 47:05.567
We have to raise several million dollars every year, but almost all that money is granted out to these programs.

47:06.028 --> 47:13.195
So we pay for half of whatever their books cost in the first year and a quarter,

47:13.478 --> 47:15.220
of the cost in subsequent years.

47:16.362 --> 47:23.771
So because that's federal money, I end up with auditors and all the people who want to know how their money was spent.

47:23.791 --> 47:36.887
So a lot of our work has to do with keeping track of sub-granting money and making sure that people are in compliance with the model to some degree or the other.

47:38.993 --> 47:47.746
take some pieces and leave some pieces, but making sure that everybody who gets some of that, federal money especially, is sort of doing the core of the program.

47:47.926 --> 48:08.376
And for us, the core is really this moment, this moment in the exam room when the doctor and the parent and the child are in there together and the doctor says to a parent, you know, do you read with your child, you know?

48:08.643 --> 48:13.368
reading aloud is probably the most important thing you can do to help them do well in school later.

48:14.669 --> 48:20.095
That moment is the core.

48:20.916 --> 48:33.790
So there are other pieces of the model, buying the books and keeping the books and giving the books at the right time and using the books as diagnostic tools and volunteers in the lobby if they can do that.

48:34.010 --> 48:36.152
But it's really that core of

48:37.212 --> 49:07.185
of a nurse or a doctor who are with a parent in the years before they have, they don't have any other authority figure, any other, often any other regular contact with anybody who's in a, I hate to use the word authority, but anyone who's important to them in a professional way and leveraging that moment to talk about reading is what Reach Out and Read does.

49:09.781 --> 49:36.510
It's a very big ask, you know, if you think that a pediatrician or a nurse practitioner has 11 minutes, 12 minutes to do an exam, to give the shots, to ask if there's any other problems, you know, to talk about seat belts and bike helmets, and we're asking them for a minute.

49:37.371 --> 49:38.011
They want one minute.

49:38.492 --> 49:38.792
Yeah.

49:39.802 --> 49:49.393
And it's a, you know, in every one of those 200, 2075 sites, it's a significant ask.

49:49.413 --> 49:50.635
We're looking for two things.

49:50.675 --> 50:00.967
You need that one minute, and for the life of the program for each individual, which is for a kid, it's from six months to five years.

50:00.987 --> 50:01.127
Uh-huh.

50:01.147 --> 50:02.348
You're looking for 25 bucks.

50:02.368 --> 50:02.569
Ten bucks.

50:02.589 --> 50:02.869
Ten bucks.

50:02.889 --> 50:03.830
Twenty-five dollars to buy.

50:03.870 --> 50:04.951
Twenty-five bucks, I guess.

50:04.971 --> 50:05.372
Twenty-five dollars.

50:05.452 --> 50:05.993
Ten bucks.

50:06.033 --> 50:06.813
Twenty-five dollars.

50:06.914 --> 50:07.294
Yeah.

50:07.730 --> 50:11.674
So really, you're not asking for a whole heck of a lot here, are you, in terms of?

50:12.976 --> 50:14.818
Not for any individual clinic.

50:14.858 --> 50:21.625
When I see it globally, where it adds into, you know, huge numbers.

50:21.705 --> 50:29.493
But it's a small, it's a small, it's a, I think we get a lot of bang for the buck.

50:29.513 --> 50:30.474
You know, the time.

50:30.494 --> 50:31.295
You're looking for the one minute.

50:31.495 --> 50:31.776
Right.

50:32.416 --> 50:36.741
But if you go to some, some HMO, like Kaiser,

50:37.531 --> 50:47.303
who measures every second of a well-child visit, and you ask them for a minute of their well-child visit, it's a huge ask.

50:49.045 --> 51:04.263
So Kaiser sees, you know, Kaiser has, we're doing business with Southern California Kaiser, which has 89 clinics and hospitals, and so you add up all the minutes we're asking for, we're asking for a lot.

51:04.283 --> 51:05.905
And every minute to them is money.

51:05.925 --> 51:06.846
Oh, yeah.

51:07.906 --> 51:26.907
and they really have to be persuaded that... As Barry says, they have to be persuaded that it's part of medicine, that literacy is part of pediatrics.

51:28.189 --> 51:32.594
Oh, he loves to talk.

51:32.614 --> 51:33.555
He's the idea man.

51:35.917 --> 51:36.478
But he...

51:36.880 --> 51:46.053
He's done very well by, first with Kaiser in Southern California and now starting a major initiative in all of Los Angeles.

51:46.073 --> 51:48.316
He's ramrodded that through, which is pretty impressive.

51:49.738 --> 51:51.740
Well, I think we've got some good stuff here.

51:51.760 --> 51:54.845
What I'm going to have to do, I want to have, this is like three hours of tape.

51:55.245 --> 52:02.836
I'm going to go back and transcribe it and then assess it and start writing this and then come back with it.

52:02.896 --> 52:03.156
Sure.

52:03.817 --> 52:05.319
Sure.

52:05.339 --> 52:06.060
And then I want to, I mean,

52:06.462 --> 52:10.409
I'm really planning to give this a nice, good run.

52:10.689 --> 52:13.695
Something like 5,000 words is a good run.

52:13.715 --> 52:14.857
Uh-huh.

52:15.879 --> 52:18.323
And a book that will be about 80,000 or 90,000 words.

52:18.343 --> 52:18.483
Uh-huh.

52:18.944 --> 52:19.906
You never have a man.

52:19.926 --> 52:20.166
Right.

52:21.148 --> 52:26.077
Well, I feel like we have... Anyway, we can get people to talk about it.

52:26.778 --> 52:28.521
Well, my books do...

52:29.615 --> 52:30.396
Right.

52:30.416 --> 52:36.882
I mean, we need help on several fronts, you know, and name recognition is great for us.

52:37.482 --> 52:46.711
Well, I know you've been written about everywhere, but I really haven't seen any of a book, a general type thing, so it's a great opportunity for me.

52:46.771 --> 52:54.678
I am bringing in a few other aspects of physicians who are being taught, medical students, the power of narrative and teaching.

52:55.299 --> 52:59.082
Yeah, that's a... How reading the classics makes them better

52:59.888 --> 53:03.092
better doctors and diagnosticians and listeners.

53:03.853 --> 53:12.342
So it's part of the whole... I'm talking to Helen Vendler at Harvard, and she's the top poetry critic in the world.

53:12.382 --> 53:14.445
Is poetry still relevant in our lives?

53:16.047 --> 53:21.873
She's a great mentor to us because she keeps us tied to the importance of reading.

53:21.893 --> 53:26.098
She always, always speaks about the love of reading.

53:26.888 --> 53:29.190
when she talks about reach out and reading.

53:29.671 --> 53:35.817
